I couldn't agree more!  I honestly think my generation (I'm 23) will be one 
of the first to reap the benefits of some of the staggeringly complex 
biomedical leaps that are in the works.  My taste in science fiction has 
changed (not "matured," by any means) from an interest in hard science to 
more "literary" sf (whatever the hell that means).

"The Diamond Age" is a fabulous book about a future that I can actually see 
happening.  "Holy Fire" by Bruce Sterling is another with this quality (which 
is rarer than some might think).  Other "hard" sf novels that have seeded me 
with progressive ideas: "Red Mars" by Kim Stanley Robinson, "Timescape" by 
Gregory Benford, "Childhood's End" by Arthur C. Clarke, "Sterling's 
"Schismatrix"...these are books that seethe with thought-food--and they're of 
"literary" quality to boot.

