If I have a cup of hot coffee sitting on the table, the water molecules
in the cup, being hot, are jiggling randomly.  There is a slight,
vanishingly small chance that the coffee will leap out of the cup and fly
up towards the ceiling.  In practice, I am highly confident this will not
happen, but in principle I cannot predict what the coffee will do with
absolute certainty.


But suppose that I knew the position and momentum of each molecule in the
cup at the present time.  Then, in principle, could I predict the future
behavior of the coffee?  Even then, I don't think so.  An errant driver
could lose control of his car, smash through the wall, hit the table, and
spill the coffee.  But neglecting the case of unpredictable external
influences, there is still a problem with predicting the future behavior
of a system.  That is that the uncertainty principle limits the precision
of measuring both the position and momentum of a particle at the same
time.  The product of the uncertainties of position and momentum is at
least Planck's constant.


So the precise initial conditions needed to make a prediction cannot be
obtained, given the uncertainty principle.


