Yes, you should pick up a text on QM.  It's not that difficult, and it's
well worth learning, IMHO.  Think of the sound metaphor.  It's really
more than a metaphor, as QM describes particles by these functions, 
which are exactly analogous to a sound wave.  Non-commuting observables
are basically Fourier transforms of each other.  With a sound wave, you
can use either an pressure amplitude vs. time or an energy amplitude vs.
frequency function to get a complete description.  But YOU CANNOT devise
a wave that will give you an *exact* time of occurence and an exact
frequency for a given sound wave.


 
