>Also, cratering is not the only way to make surface features -- even on
>Mars.  Thus, the alternatives aren't either it's a crater or some
>intelligent being(s) made it.

It's been demonstrated that the features in question (Crater Pyramid and 
Cliff) must have formed after the crater was formed (in fact, it's really 
obvious in the Cliff's case, since the meteor impacted when Cydonia was wet, 
or melted enough permafrost to cause a big "splash" of mud).  So the impact 
itself didn't form these (or even scar them).  I'm not saying they have to be 
artificial.  But I haven't heard any good argument to explain, say, the 
proximity of the Crater Pyramid with its neighboring crater.  The best I've 
heard, actually, is "giant crystal growth," which I find quite ridiculous.  
